  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and principles for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing of financial intelligence and evidence across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Standardized reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting protocols\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering offenses\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International monitoring and evaluation processes\n- Peer review systems\n- Sanctions for non-compliance with global standards\n\n5. Information Sharing Networks\n- Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- International criminal databases\n- Cross-border collaboration in tracking financial crimes\n\n6. Harmonization of Legal Approaches\n- Gradual convergence of national legal frameworks\n- Consistent interpretation of money laundering definitions\n- Alignment of investigative and prosecutorial strategies\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to combating international financial crime.",
